From 729e1d1252929eea93df257dba948557d1d5975e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: apannerselva <apannerselva@marvell.com>
Date: Tue, 31 Mar 2026 22:25:00 +0530
Subject: [PATCH] EVPN MH kernel patch

Why I did it
=============
This PR adds three critical Linux kernel patches required to enable
EVPN VXLAN Multihoming in SONiC. These kernel enhancements provide
the necessary infrastructure for:

- Extended neighbor flags for multi-homing peer synchronization
- Protocol field tracking in bridge FDB entries to distinguish
  control plane vs data plane learned MACs
- External validation flag to prevent kernel from invalidating
  externally managed neighbor entries

These patches are essential for implementing the EVPN-MH feature
as described in the EVPN VXLAN Multihoming HLD.

How I did it
=============
Added three kernel patches to patches-sonic directory:

1. NDA_FLAGS_EXT Support with NTF_EXT_MH_PEER_SYNC
   (0001-vxlan-bridge-Add-NDA_FLAGS_EXT-support-with-NTF_EXT_.patch)

   Adds extended flags support for VXLAN and bridge FDB entries to
   enable multi-homing peer synchronization:
   - New field: ext_flags in vxlan_fdb structure
   - New flag: NTF_EXT_MH_PEER_SYNC - Indicates FDB entry is
     synchronized across EVPN-MH peers
   - New neighbor update flag: NEIGH_UPDATE_F_EXT_MH_PEER_SYNC
   - Modified functions: vxlan_fdb_alloc(), vxlan_fdb_create(),
     vxlan_fdb_update_existing(), vxlan_fdb_update_create(),
     vxlan_fdb_info(), and bridge FDB functions
   - Files: drivers/net/vxlan/vxlan_core.c, vxlan_private.h,
     vxlan_vnifilter.c, include/net/neighbour.h,
     include/uapi/linux/neighbour.h, net/bridge/br.c, br_fdb.c,
     br_private.h, net/core/neighbour.c

2. Protocol Field in Bridge FDB
   (0001-net-bridge-vxlan-Protocol-field-in-bridge-fdb.patch)

   Introduces an optional "protocol" field for bridge FDB entries to
   distinguish between control plane and data plane learned MACs:
   - Control plane (ZEBRA protocol): Static MACs distributed by FRR/BGP
   - Data plane (HW protocol): Dynamic MACs learned from traffic
   - Enables proper state machine management during MAC transitions,
     traffic hashing between EVPN-MH peers, MAC mobility handling,
     and control/data plane synchronization
   - New field: protocol in net_bridge_fdb_entry and vxlan_fdb
   - Default: RTPROT_UNSPEC when not specified (backward compatible)
   - Files: drivers/net/vxlan/vxlan_core.c, vxlan_private.h,
     vxlan_vnifilter.c, net/bridge/br.c, br_fdb.c, br_private.h

3. NTF_EXT_VALIDATED Flag for External Validation
   (0001-neighbor-Add-NTF_EXT_VALIDATED-flag-for-externally-v.patch)

   Adds "extern_valid" neighbor flag for entries learned and validated
   externally that should not be invalidated by the kernel:
   - In EVPN-MH, neighbor entries are distributed to ES peers using
     EVPN MAC/IP advertisement routes
   - Based on draft-rbickhart-evpn-ip-mac-proxy-adv-03
   - ES peers install neighbor entries and inject proxy advertisements
   - When ES link goes down, peers start aging timers instead of
     immediately withdrawing (prevents intermittent routing failures)
   - Kernel will NOT remove or invalidate extern_valid entries
   - Control plane (FRR) manages entry lifecycle
   - Files: neighbor subsystem, netlink attributes, state machine

How to verify it
=================
Build kernel with these patches applied:
  cd sonic-linux-kernel
  make BLDENV=bookworm

Verify NDA_FLAGS_EXT support:
  bridge fdb add <mac> dev <vxlan-dev> dst <vtep-ip> vni <vni> extern_learn
  bridge -d fdb show | grep <mac>

Verify protocol field support:
  bridge fdb add <mac> dev <device> vlan <vid> master dynamic extern_learn proto hw
  bridge -d fdb show dev <device> | grep <mac>
  # Expected output includes: proto hw
  bridge fdb replace <mac> dev <device> vlan <vid> master dynamic extern_learn proto zebra
  # Expected output includes: proto zebra

Verify extern_valid flag:
  # Neighbor entries with extern_valid remain in "stale" state
  ip -d neigh show

Integration testing with EVPN-MH:
  - Configure EVPN multi-homing with ES peers
  - Verify MAC/neighbor synchronization across peers
  - Test ES link failure scenarios
  - Verify proxy advertisements and aging behavior
  - Confirm no intermittent routing/ARP failures during transitions
  - Verify existing bridge/VXLAN functionality (backward compatible)

